      "text": "Here\u0027s the English translation of the provided Dhivehi text:\n\n**Laws of the Maldives**\n\n**Law on Urban Planning and Development**\n\n**Law on Urban Planning and Development**\n\n**Chapter One**\n**Introduction**\n\n**Definitions and Name**\n**1.**\n(a) This is a law to establish a robust legal framework for urban planning and development at the national, city, and regional levels, ensuring that land in the Maldives is utilized in a sustainable and responsible manner. It outlines the principles of urban planning and development, and the concepts for sustainable urban development in accordance with the plans formulated by planning authorities.\n(b) This law shall be called the \"Law on Urban Planning and Development\".\n\n**Objectives**\n**2.**\nThe objectives of this law are set out below:\n(a) To facilitate urban planning for the economic, social, and environmental development and management of land in the Maldives in an appropriate manner;\n(b) To establish principles for urban planning and development in the Maldives in a manner that facilitates sustainable land use and responsible land utilization;\n(c) To establish principles for urban planning and development in a manner that facilitates the decentralized development of the administrative divisions of the Maldives;\n(d) To facilitate the work of parties assigned various responsibilities under this law in a manner that achieves the objectives of urban planning in the fulfillment of their responsibilities;\n(e) To establish a system for monitoring the work of land developers and holding them accountable, to ensure the effective enforcement of the law;\n(f) To facilitate increased public participation in the stages of urban planning and development.\n\n**Chapter Two**\n**Implementation of the Law**\n\n**Urban Planning and Development Policy**\n**3.**\n(a) The national policy on urban planning and development shall be determined by the President, upon the recommendation of the Cabinet of Ministers.\n(b) The national policy on urban planning and development shall be determined and publicized under subsection (a) of this Article.\n(c) The Minister shall bear the primary responsibility for the enforcement of this law, by ensuring that planning authorities and other relevant parties effectively carry out their duties in implementing the national policy on urban planning and development determined under subsection (a) of this Article.\n\n**Responsibilities of the Ministry**\n**4.**\nThe responsibilities of the Ministry in enforcing this law are set out below:\n(a) To formulate and enforce regulations and guidelines required under this law concerning the utilization and development of land in the Maldives;\n(b) To ensure that plans formulated by planning authorities are in accordance with this law and regulations made hereunder, and to ensure the implementation of these plans;\n(c) To register planners active in urban planning in the Maldives and maintain a registry of these parties;\n(d) To provide advice to planning authorities on matters requiring technical assistance;\n(e) To take action against parties in violation of this law and regulations made hereunder;\n(f) To review decisions of planning authorities and make decisions on submitted issues;\n(g) To evaluate the extent of the implementation of this law and to compile and publish relevant statistics and reports.\n\n**Formation of Committees, Panels, and Working Groups**\n**5.**\n(a) The Minister shall have the authority to form technical committees, panels, or working groups in accordance with regulations made under this law, to provide technical advice to the Ministry on matters related to urban planning and development.\n(b) Technical committees, panels, or working groups formed under this Article shall include technical representatives from the Ministry and relevant government agencies, as well as representatives from civil society organizations and/or private sector entities.\n(c) The following matters relating to technical committees, panels, or working groups formed under this Article shall be specified in regulations made under this law:\n(1) The fields in which committee, panel, or working group members should have expertise, and the procedures and regulations for appointing members to such committees;\n(2) The purpose for which a committee, panel, or working group is formed, and the responsibilities assigned to such committee, panel, or working group;\n(3) The manner in which committee, panel, or working group meetings will be held, and the principles to be followed by the committee, panel, or working group in making decisions;\n(4) The operational principles of committees, panels, or working groups, and other related matters.\n\n**Planning Authorities**\n**6.**\n(a) The responsibility for formulating urban plans, approving these plans, and overseeing their implementation, as well as issuing permits for land development in accordance with the plans, is entrusted to the planning authorities specified in subsection (b) of this Article, in accordance with this law.\n(b) For the purposes of this law, the following authorities shall be considered as planning authorities:\n(1) The Ministry;\n(2) City Council;\n(3) Island Council;\n(4) Authorities designated for planning urban areas;\n(5) Authorities designated for planning industrial areas;\n(6) Authorities designated for planning special economic zones.\n(c) The following matters relating to the authorities specified in subsection (b) of this Article shall be stipulated in regulations made under this law:\n(1) The powers that may be delegated to a specific planning authority, and the conditions and circumstances under which these powers can be exercised;\n(2) Other matters deemed important for a planning authority to exercise its powers granted by this law in the most effective and cost-efficient manner.\n(d) Except for special areas developed under specific laws relating to the planning and development of a particular type of area, for other areas, the Ministry may determine, in accordance with regulations made under this law, whether a specific planning authority\u0027s jurisdiction includes more than one planning area or a specific part of a planning area.\n(e) In circumstances where the jurisdiction of a specific planning authority is determined as per subsection (d) of this Article, and the area in which the authority\u0027s jurisdiction operates for the enforcement of this law, shall be published in the Government Gazette.\n\n**Responsibilities of Planning Authorities**\n**7.**\nThe responsibilities of planning authorities in enforcing this law are set out below:\n(a) To formulate a physical development plan for the island, city, or area within the jurisdiction of a planning authority;\n(b) To submit the physical development plan to the Ministry for approval and to make amendments to the plan as directed by the Ministry;\n(c) To review applications for permits for development within the jurisdiction of a planning authority, and to make decisions on these applications;\n(d) To ensure that all aspects of urban development and management within the jurisdiction of a planning authority are carried out in accordance with the approved plans under the law, and to enforce these plans;\n(e) To investigate complaints submitted to a planning authority under this law and take action.\n\n**Chapter Three**\n**Physical Development Plan**\n\n**Physical Development Plan**\n**8.**\n(a) Planning authorities shall formulate a physical development plan for the area within their jurisdiction to facilitate the planned, sustainable, and responsible development of land in the Maldives.\n(b) A physical development plan formulated under this Article shall be a master plan that defines the locations for the establishment of key spatial components required for the development of an island, city, or area, the criteria to be considered in determining these locations, and other related aspects of land and physical resources for that area. It shall include the planning and determination of residential areas, industrial and economic zones, public spaces and facilities for public use, and locations for the establishment of infrastructure within that island, city, or area. Furthermore, it shall encompass the planning of urban development for that island, city, or area, and the planning of how to manage and protect its natural resources, cultural heritage, and environment.\n(c) The main objective of a physical development plan is to provide guidance for the long-term natural progress and development of a particular island, city, or area.\n\n**Types of Plans**\n**9.**\nThe physical development plans referred to in Article 8 of this law include the following plans:\n(a) Regional Development Master Plan; This is a plan formulated by the designated authority for a region determined by the government\u0027s policy for decentralized development of the Maldives, for the planning and development of that region.\n(b) City Development Master Plan; This is a plan formulated by the City Council for a designated city or area that is a recognized city.\n(c) Island Development Master Plan; This is a plan formulated by the Island Council for a designated inhabited island.\n(d) Urban Area Development Master Plan; This is a plan formulated by the authority designated under relevant laws for a region designated as an urban area for development.\n(e) Industrial Area Development Master Plan; This is a plan formulated by the authority designated by the government for the planning and development of islands and areas designated as industrial areas.\n(f) Commercial Area Development Master Plan; This is a plan formulated by the authority designated by the government for the planning and development of islands and areas designated for tourism resort development or other special economic purposes, which are not industrial areas.\n\n**Considerations in Formulating Plans**\n**10.**\n(a) Physical development plans for islands, cities, urban areas, and areas developed for industrial or economic purposes in the Maldives shall be formulated in accordance with the objectives set out in the National Development Plan of the Maldives. These plans shall also be formulated in accordance with the standards specified in the regulations made under this law.\n(b) Planning authorities shall formulate physical development plans in a manner that minimizes the negative impact on the natural and human environment of the island, city, or area for which the plan is being formulated. Accordingly, special attention shall be given to the following matters and their preservation:\n(1) Agricultural activities;\n(2) Fishing, aquaculture, and mariculture activities;\n(3) Urban infrastructure;\n(4) Industrial activities;\n(5) Environmental protection;\n(6) Natural resources;\n(7) Historical buildings;\n(8) Habitation environment;\n(9) Tourism.\n\n**Formulation of Plans through Registered Parties**\n**11.**\n(a) Physical development plans formulated by planning authorities under this law shall be formulated through a registered planner.\n(b) The qualifications of planners referred to in subsection (a) of this Article, and the principles for registering and classifying planners, shall be specified in regulations made under this law.\n\n**Seeking Opinion and Consultation in Plan Formulation**\n**12.**\n(a) The physical development plan for a specific city or island shall be formulated in consultation with the public of that city or island.\n(b) The physical development plan for urban areas, special economic zones, or areas designated for industrial projects shall be formulated in consultation with the local councils of those areas.\n\n**Plan Approval**\n**13.**\n(a) Physical development plans formulated by planning authorities under this law shall be implemented only after their approval in accordance with this law and regulations made hereunder.\n(b) After formulating plans under this law, planning authorities shall submit them to the Ministry for approval.\n(c) Plans formulated under this law shall be submitted to the Ministry for approval, along with the signature of a registered planner, in accordance with the procedures specified in regulations made under this law.\n(d) When submitting plans to the Ministry for approval under subsection (b) of this Article, planning authorities shall submit the information and documents required by the regulations made under this law, as specified in the regulations made under this law.\n(e) The regulations made under this law may require planning authorities to prepare and submit impact assessments and other technical analyses and reports that will assist in the approval and/or implementation of plans.\n(f) If a plan submitted for approval under subsection (b) of this Article fulfills all requirements stipulated in this law and regulations made hereunder, the Ministry shall approve and pass the plan within a maximum of ninety (90) days from the date of submission.\n(g) If the Ministry is not satisfied that a plan submitted for approval under subsection (b) of this Article fulfills all requirements stipulated in this law and regulations made hereunder, it shall notify the planning authority that submitted the plan within a maximum of sixty (60) days from the date of submission, indicating the deficiencies or areas needing correction. After completing or correcting these aspects, the planning authority will be given a minimum of thirty (30) days to resubmit the plan for approval.\n(h) If, after completion or correction of the matters specified in subsection (g) of this Article, a plan is resubmitted and fulfills all requirements for plan approval under this law, the Ministry shall approve and pass the plan within a maximum of thirty (30) days from the date of resubmission of the revised plan.\n(i) If a plan submitted for approval under this Article is formulated in contravention of, or in conflict with, the principles and standards specified in this law and regulations made hereunder, the Ministry shall not approve the plan and shall inform the planning authority that submitted the plan to revise and resubmit it.\n(j) If the Ministry decides not to approve a plan submitted for approval under this Article, it shall inform the planning authority that submitted the plan in writing, within the period specified in subsection (f) of this Article, stating the detailed reasons for non-approval.\n(k) If the Ministry does not make a decision regarding a plan submitted for approval under subsections (f) or (g) of this Article within the specified periods, and if the submission fulfills all requirements stipulated by this law and regulations made hereunder, the plan shall be considered approved.\n\n**Review of Plans**\n**14.**\nIf, after a plan has been approved by the Ministry under this law, an amendment is found to be necessary in a part of the approved plan, the Ministry shall inform the planning authority that formulated the plan, stating the reasons, and in accordance with the procedures specified in regulations made under this law, instruct them to review the plan and submit the amended part for approval.\n\n**Amendment to Plans**\n**15.**\n(a) If, after a plan has been formulated and approved under this law, changes are necessary to the plan or a part thereof due to changes in the area to which the plan pertains, the required amendments shall be prepared in accordance with the procedures specified in regulations made under this law, and these amendments shall be submitted for approval in accordance with Article 13 of this law.\n(b) The regulations made under this law shall define the use of individual plans included in a physical development plan, the procedures to be followed in formulating these plans, and the basic information that must be included in the plans.\n\n**Surveying**\n**16.**\nSurveys for the preparation of plans formulated under this law shall be conducted in accordance with the standards stipulated in the Land Law and regulations made hereunder.\n\n**Chapter Four**\n**Development Controls**\n\n**Part One**\n**Permit for Land Development**\n\n**Application for Permit for Land Development**\n**17.**\n(a) Any land in the Maldives shall be developed only after obtaining a permit for land development in accordance with the provisions of this Chapter.\n(b) Applications for permits for land development in a city or island shall be submitted to the council of that city or island.\n(c) Applications for permits for land development in areas other than cities or islands shall be submitted to the Ministry.\n(d) The information and documents that must be submitted to planning authorities along with an application for a permit for land development under this Article shall be specified in regulations made under this law.\n(e) When issuing a permit for land development, the issuing authority shall ensure that the proposed development work on the land is carried out in accordance with the applicable laws and regulations related to that work and/or its execution.\n(f) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this Article, if a specific law governing the planning and development of a particular type of land or area stipulates specific procedures for the issuance of development permits, then the procedures stipulated in that specific law shall apply to the development of such land or area.\n\n**Acts Not Constituting Development**\n**18.**\n(a) For the purposes of this Chapter, if a change in the use of land occurs, and the proposed use is of the same category as the previous use, such a change in land use shall not be considered as land development.\n(b) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this Article, the following types of actions that constitute a significant change in the use of land shall not be considered as exceptions:\n(1) The dumping of hazardous waste or other discarded materials in a designated waste disposal area;\n(2) The conversion of a residential dwelling into a garage or for commercial purposes;\n(3) Other matters determined by the Ministry to constitute a significant change in land use, and as specified in regulations made under this law.\n\n**Issuance of Permit for Land Development**\n**19.**\n(a) If a planning authority is satisfied that an application for a permit for land development submitted under Article 17 of this law meets all the requirements stipulated in this law and regulations made hereunder, the permit shall be issued within a maximum of thirty (30) days from the date of submission.\n(b) In issuing a permit for land development under subsection (a) of this Article, the planning authority may decide to grant the permit without additional conditions, or with conditions as specified in Article 20 of this law.\n(c) If a planning authority is not satisfied that an application for a permit for land development submitted under Article 17 of this law meets all the requirements stipulated in this law and regulations made hereunder, it shall notify the applicant within a maximum of fifteen (15) days from the date of submission, indicating the deficiencies or areas needing correction. After completing or correcting these aspects, the applicant will be given a minimum of fifteen (15) days to resubmit the application for approval.\n(d) If, after completion or correction of the matters specified in subsection (c) of this Article, an application for a permit for land development is resubmitted and fulfills all requirements for the issuance of the permit under this law, the permit shall be issued within a maximum of fifteen (15) days from the date of resubmission of the revised application.\n(e) If an application for a permit for land development submitted under this Article is formulated in contravention of, or in conflict with, the principles and standards specified in this law and regulations made hereunder, the planning authority has the power to refuse to issue the permit for land development.\n(f) If a planning authority decides not to issue a permit for land development under subsection (e) of this Article, it shall inform the applicant in writing, within the period specified in subsection (a) of this Article, stating the detailed reasons for refusal.\n(g) If a decision is not made on an application for a permit for land development under this Article within the thirty (30) day period specified in subsection (a), or if the period is extended, the planning authority shall inform the applicant in writing of the extended period and the reasons for the extension.\n(h) If an application for a permit for land development is submitted and fulfills all requirements stipulated by this law and regulations made hereunder, the permit shall be considered issued if no decision is made by the planning authority within the periods specified in subsections (a) or (c) of this Article.\n\n**Determination of Additional Conditions**\n**20.**\nWhen issuing a permit for land development, the planning authority has the power to impose any of the following conditions, or a combination thereof, to ensure the optimal development of the land to which the permit pertains:\n(a) Preservation of archaeological buildings that are essential to be protected in the area of development;\n(b) Ensuring that development activities are carried out in a manner that protects the landscape, protected trees, and other natural resources present on or adjacent to the land designated for development;\n(c) Protection of existing buildings or adjacent buildings in the development area;\n(d) Implementation of measures required by an environmental impact assessment conducted in accordance with relevant laws, concerning any environmental damage that may result from development activities;\n(e) Conducting a social impact assessment to evaluate potential social changes or damages resulting from land development, and implementing the measures mandated by that assessment;\n(f) Conducting a transport assessment to evaluate potential changes or damages to the transportation system resulting from land development, and implementing the measures mandated by that assessment.\n\n**Period for Completion of Development**\n**21.**\n(a) When issuing a permit for land development, a specific period for the completion of the development work shall be stipulated in the permit.\n(b) Notwithstanding the period specified in the permit for land development under subsection (a) of this Article, if the actual development work has not commenced within one (1) year from the date of issuance of the permit, the permit shall be invalidated.\n(c) If a party to whom a permit for land development has been issued wishes to extend the period granted for development under subsection (a) of this Article, they shall submit a written request to the planning authority, stating the reasons why the development work cannot be completed within the granted period.\n(d) If an extension of time is requested under subsection (c) of this Article, the planning authority that issued the permit has the discretion to grant an extension of the permit period in accordance with the regulations made under this law.\n\n**Making Regulations for the Issuance of Permits for Land Development**\n**22.**\nRegulations made under this law shall specify the matters to be considered by planning authorities when issuing permits for land development, the criteria for issuing permits, the types of permits, the information to be included in permits, and other related principles and procedures.\n\n**Part Two**\n**Compliance**\n\n**Compliance with the Law**\n**23.**\n(a) The holder of a permit for land development issued under Article 19 of this law, and any party holding such a permit, shall comply with the conditions and timeframes stipulated in the permit, and with the development standards set forth in this law and regulations made hereunder.\n(b) If the holder of a permit for land development issued by a planning authority does not comply with the permit and its conditions and timeframes, or with the development standards specified in this law and regulations made hereunder, or if development work is carried out without obtaining a permit for land development, it shall be considered a violation of development controls.\n\n**Imposition of Measures**\n**24.**\nParties carrying out development activities in violation of this law may be subject to the following measures, or any of these measures:\n(a) Issuance of a warning notice;\n(b) Issuance of a compliance notice;\n(c) Issuance of a stop-work notice;\n(d) Imposition of fines.\n\n**Issuance of Warning Notice**\n**25.**\n(a) If a planning authority finds that any party has violated development controls, it shall issue a warning notice to the owner of the land and the occupants of the land within two (2) years from the date of commencement of unauthorized work or from the date of violation of the permit.\n(b) If a warning notice has been issued under subsection (a) of this Article for a violation of development controls, no further action shall be taken by the planning authority before the expiry of the period specified in the notice.\n(c) The maximum period for which a planning authority may issue a warning notice under subsection (a) of this Article is thirty (30) days.\n(d) The information to be included in the warning notice and the notifications to be given to the parties receiving the notice shall be specified in regulations made under this law.\n(e) If a violation of development controls comes to the notice of a planning authority more than two (2) years after the work was carried out, the planning authority shall not have the right to issue a notice under this Article and take any action to rectify the work.\n\n**Compliance Notice**\n**26.**\n(a) Planning authorities may issue a compliance notice to the holder of a development permit in the following circumstances:\n(1) Violation of development controls; or\n(2) Violation of a physical development plan approved under this law.\n(b) A compliance notice issued under subsection (a) of this Article shall clearly state the following:\n(1) The matters identified by the planning authority as violations of development controls or physical development plans;\n(2) The measures to be taken by the permit holder to rectify the matters specified in paragraph (1) of this subsection, and the measures that must be taken within a maximum of twenty (20) days;\n(3) The need to comply with the compliance notice within a maximum of forty (40) days from the date of issuance of the compliance notice.\n\n**Revocation of Compliance Notice**\n**27.**\n(a) The party to whom a compliance notice is issued may apply to the planning authority that issued the notice for the revocation of the notice within twenty (20) days of receiving it.\n(b) In accordance with subsection (a) of this Article, after reviewing an application for the revocation of a compliance notice submitted under Article 33 of this law, the planning authority may decide to postpone the enforcement of the notice, amend the notice, or withdraw the notice.\n(c) If the planning authority decides that it is not possible to act upon the notice in any of the ways specified in subsection (b) of this Article, it may decide that the notice is valid and that the revocation cannot be granted.\n(d) In accordance with subsection (a) of this Article, the planning authority shall make a decision regarding an application for the revocation of a compliance notice under Article 33 of this law within a maximum of fifteen (15) days from the date of receipt of the application, and shall inform the applicant of the decision.\n(e) The procedure for applying for the revocation of a notice and the principles to be followed by planning authorities in making decisions on such applications shall be specified in regulations made under this law.\n\n**Stop-Work Notice**\n**28.**\n(a) If a party to whom a compliance notice has been issued under Article 26 of this law fails to comply with the notice within the specified period, the planning authority shall issue a stop-work notice to that party to cease the development work.\n(b) The stop-work notice under subsection (a) of this Article shall be issued to the owner of the land and all parties responsible for the violation of development controls or physical development plans.\n(c) The occupants of the land shall be informed of the issuance of the stop-work notice under subsection (a) of this Article.\n(d) The stop-work notice issued under this Article shall include the following:\n(1) A copy of the compliance notice related to the action in question;\n(2) An instruction to cease the violation of development controls or physical development plans, and the period allowed for ceasing such violation (which shall be a maximum of forty-eight (48) hours);\n(3) The measures that will be taken if the instruction in the notice is not complied with within the specified period;\n(4) The right of the party receiving the notice to apply for the revocation of the notice under Article 33 of this law.\n\n**Application for Permit to Resume Work**\n**29.**\n(a) The party to whom a stop-work notice has been issued under Article 28 of this law shall comply with the notice and cease work within the period specified in the notice.\n(b) A party to whom a stop-work notice has been issued may resume work only after rectifying all the issues specified for correction in the compliance notice issued under Article 26 of this law, and after applying for and obtaining a permit to resume work from the planning authority.\n(c) The procedures to be followed by parties whose development work has been stopped by planning authorities, and the principles to be followed by planning authorities in issuing such permits to resume work, shall be specified in regulations made under this law.\n\n**Penalty for Non-Compliance with Compliance Notice**\n**30.**\nIf a party fails to comply with a compliance notice issued under Article 26 of this law, the planning authority may impose a fine on that party as follows:\n(a) If the value of the development work or project to which the notice pertains is less than MVR 10,000,000 (Ten Million Rufiyaa), a fine of between MVR 1,000 (One Thousand Rufiyaa) and MVR 10,000 (Ten Thousand Rufiyaa);\n(b) If the value of the development work or project to which the notice pertains is greater than MVR 10,000,000 (Ten Million Rufiyaa), a fine of between MVR 10,000 (Ten Thousand Rufiyaa) and MVR 50,000 (Fifty Thousand Rufiyaa);\n(c) For each subsequent instance of non-compliance with a compliance notice for the same issue, a fine of between MVR 100,000 (One Hundred Thousand Rufiyaa) and MVR 200,000 (Two Hundred Thousand Rufiyaa).\n\n**Penalty for Non-Compliance with Stop-Work Notice**\n**31.**\nIf a party fails to comply with a stop-work notice issued under Article 28 of this law, the planning authority may impose a fine on that party as follows:\n(a) If the value of the development work or project to which the notice pertains is less than MVR 10,000,000 (Ten Million Rufiyaa), a fine of between MVR 1,000 (One Thousand Rufiyaa) and MVR 10,000 (Ten Thousand Rufiyaa);\n(b) If the value of the development work or project to which the notice pertains is greater than MVR 10,000,000 (Ten Million Rufiyaa), a fine of between MVR 10,000 (Ten Thousand Rufiyaa) and MVR 50,000 (Fifty Thousand Rufiyaa);\n(c) For each subsequent instance of non-compliance with a stop-work notice for the same issue, a fine of between MVR 150,000 (One Hundred and Fifty Thousand Rufiyaa) and MVR 250,000 (Two Hundred and Fifty Thousand Rufiyaa); and\n(d) In addition to the fines specified in subsections (a), (b), and (c) of this Article, a fine of not exceeding MVR 1,000 (One Thousand Rufiyaa) per day for each day that the stop-work notice is not complied with.\n\n**Enforcement of Notices**\n**32.**\n(a) To verify compliance with compliance notices or stop-work notices, authorized officers of the planning authority may enter and inspect the premises at any reasonable time of the day, upon providing 48 (forty-eight) hours\u0027 notice.\n(b) If, during an inspection under subsection (a) of this Article, it is found that the parties who received the compliance notice have not taken adequate measures, or that the parties who received the stop-work notice have not ceased work in accordance with the notice, the planning authority or its designated representative shall have the power to take further measures in accordance with the regulations made under this law to enforce the measures specified in the compliance notice or to stop the work as per the stop-work notice.\n(c) The costs incurred by the planning authority or its designated representative in taking measures to enforce a compliance notice or a stop-work notice shall be borne by the party to whom the compliance notice or stop-work notice was issued.\n(d) If the premises to be inspected under subsection (a) of this Article is a residential dwelling, entry shall be made only after obtaining the permission of the owner of the premises, or through a court order if such permission cannot be obtained.\n(e) Before entering the premises under subsection (a) of this Article, the notice shall state the reason for entry and the estimated time required for the inspection.\n(f) The authorized officer conducting the inspection under this Article must possess official written authorization from the planning authority. This authorization shall be presented to the owner of the land or any party with an interest in the land upon request.\n(g) An authorized officer entering and inspecting land or premises shall not cause any damage to the land or any property therein. The planning authority shall be liable for any damage caused by its officer during such inspection.\n\n**Chapter Five**\n**Submission of Complaints and Adjudication of Disputes**\n\n**Submission of Complaints to Planning Authorities**\n**33.**\nAny party with a legitimate interest has the right to submit a complaint to a planning authority in relation to the following matters:\n(a) Refusal to grant a permit for land development, or granting a permit for land development with or without conditions;\n(b) Amendment or notice of cancellation of a permit for land development;\n(c) Issuance of a compliance notice or a stop-work notice to a party undertaking development work;\n(d) A decision by a planning authority not to issue a compliance notice or a stop-work notice to a particular party, which adversely affects the interests of another party;\n(e) Any decision made by a planning authority, other than those specified in subsections (a) to (d) of this Article, which adversely affects the interests of that party;\n(f) Any violation of this law or regulations made hereunder by any party, which results in harm to that party.\n\n**Submission and Adjudication of Complaints**\n**34.**\n(a) The procedures for submitting complaints to planning authorities, the principles for adjudicating complaints, and the measures to be taken by planning authorities following the adjudication of complaints shall be specified in regulations made under this law. The regulations shall also specify the period within which planning authorities must adjudicate complaints submitted under Article 33 of this law.\n(b) Planning authorities shall establish a system for adjudicating complaints submitted under Article 33 of this law and form the necessary committees for complaint adjudication within sixty (60) days from the date this law comes into force. Planning authorities shall also make arrangements to facilitate the submission of complaints by parties.\n(c) If a planning authority, based on sound reasoning, determines that a complaint submitted by any party is unfounded, it shall inform the complainant in writing of the decision and the reasons thereof within seven (7) days of making the decision.\n(d) Unless otherwise provided in this law, a complaint under Article 33 of this law must be submitted within thirty (30) days from the date of the action giving rise to the complaint.\n\n**Proactive Adjudication of Disputes by Planning Authorities**\n**35.**\nPlanning authorities may proactively investigate the following types of issues:\n(a) Matters where a planning authority believes any party has violated this law or standards set under this law;\n(b) Matters where a planning authority believes any party has acted in contravention of instructions issued by the Ministry or a planning authority, or any other law, in accordance with this law; and\n(c) Any other matter that a planning authority deems necessary to investigate based on sound reasoning.\n\n**Procedures for Adjudicating Complaints**\n**36.**\nIn adjudicating matters and complaints under Article 33 and Article 35 of this law, the planning authority shall follow the following procedures:\n(a) To notify the party who submitted the matter or complaint in writing that the matter or complaint has been registered with the planning authority;\n(b) To provide the party against whom the matter is raised with an opportunity to respond; and\n(c) Upon completion of the investigation, to inform the party who submitted the matter and the party against whom the matter is raised in writing of the planning authority\u0027s decision.\n\n**Report on the Outcome of the Case**\n**37.**\n(a) After investigating a matter under Article 33 and Article 35 of this law, the planning authority shall prepare a report.\n(b) The report prepared under subsection (a) of this Article shall include the following:\n(1) The process of investigating the matter;\n(2) The findings of the committee during the investigation;\n(3) The evidence on which the information and findings in paragraph (2) of this subsection are based;\n(4) The planning authority\u0027s opinions or recommendations regarding the matter, or its decision on the matter.\n\n**Review of Planning Authority Decisions**\n**38.**\n(a) Any party dissatisfied with a decision made by a planning authority in relation to a complaint submitted under Article 33 of this law, or in relation to a proactive investigation of a matter under Article 35 of this law, has the right to appeal that decision to the Ministry.\n(b) The procedures for appealing a planning authority\u0027s decision under subsection (a) of this Article and the principles to be followed in the appeal process shall be specified in regulations made under this law.\n(c) A review committee shall be established within the Ministry to adjudicate appeals submitted under this Article.\n\n**Submission of Matters to the Judiciary**\n**39.**\n(a) If a party is dissatisfied with a decision made by the Ministry\u0027s review committee under Article 38 of this law, and if the reasons stated in the notification of the decision are not satisfactory to the party, that party has the right to submit the matter to the judiciary within thirty (30) days of receiving the notification.\n(b) The right of any party to submit a matter to the judiciary under subsection (a) of this Article shall be exercised only after fulfilling the procedures specified in the regulations made under Article 38 of this law.\n\n**Chapter Six**\n**Miscellaneous Provisions**\n\n**Disclosure of Information**\n**40.**\n(a) Planning authorities shall make public information related to physical development plans approved under this law and permits for development issued under this law, in accordance with the procedures specified in regulations made under this law.\n(b) If a planning authority or the Ministry deems it necessary to publicize information regarding any notice or decision issued under this law that affects any party, such information shall be publicized in accordance with the procedures specified in regulations made under this law.\n(c) The reports prepared by committees formed by planning authorities under subsection (b) of Article 34, after investigating matters, shall be made public and published in accordance with Article 37 of this law.\n(d) Notwithstanding subsections (a), (b), and (c) of this Article, information and reports specified therein, or parts thereof, shall not be made public or disclosed in the following circumstances:\n(1) If the disclosure of such information or report, or part thereof, would reveal a trade secret of an individual or company; or\n(2) If it could impede an ongoing investigation related to a criminal matter; or\n(3) If it could impede the administration of justice in a legal proceeding against an individual; or\n(4) If it could endanger national security.\n(e) When disclosing any information under this Article, if it contains any personal or private information of an individual, that portion of the information shall be redacted to the extent that it does not reveal such information, and the remaining part of the information shall be disclosed.\n\n**Levying of Fees or Charges**\n**41.**\nPlanning authorities may levy fees or charges in connection with the services provided by them under this law, as specified in regulations made by the Ministry under this law.\n\n**Procedure for Sending Notices**\n**42.**\nThe procedures for delivering any notice required to be sent to any party under this law, and the principles for determining when such notice is deemed to have been delivered, shall be specified in regulations made under this law.\n\n**Legal Protection**\n**43.**\n(a) No civil or criminal proceedings shall be brought against any employee of the Ministry or a planning authority, or any person acting under the direction of the Ministry or a planning authority, in respect of any act done or omitted to be done in good faith in the course of carrying out their duties or exercising powers conferred by this law, in accordance with the law or within the scope of powers conferred by law.\n(b) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this Article, an employee acting under the direction of the Ministry or a planning authority shall be liable for any loss caused by their intentional act or negligence, in accordance with the applicable laws and regulations.\n\n**Other Enforcement Measures**\n**44.**\nIn addition to the fines specified in Article 30 or Article 31 of this law for violations of compliance notices or stop-work notices, the Ministry has the authority to impose fines on parties who violate this law and regulations made hereunder, as follows:\n(a) If the violator is an individual, a fine not exceeding MVR 15,000 (Fifteen Thousand Rufiyaa). If the violation is repeated, a fine not exceeding MVR 50,000 (Fifty Thousand Rufiyaa);\n(b) If the violator is a legal entity, a fine not exceeding MVR 30,000 (Thirty Thousand Rufiyaa). If the violation is repeated, a fine not exceeding MVR 100,000 (One Hundred Thousand Rufiyaa);\n(c) If a planning authority acts in contravention of a plan approved by the Ministry, a fine not exceeding MVR 50,000 (Fifty Thousand Rufiyaa).\n\n**Continuing Provisions**\n**45.**\nAt the commencement of this law, any directive, notice, instruction, condition, permit, approved plan, or any other decision issued or made by a government agency in relation to planning shall be deemed to be a decision made in accordance with this law, provided it is not in conflict with this law.\n\n**Application of Other Laws**\n**46.**\n(a) In carrying out their responsibilities, the Ministry and planning authorities shall comply with any other laws that require them to consider specific matters, in addition to the provisions of this law.\n(b) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in this law, for the planning and development of urban areas, the principles outlined in the Urban Development Law shall take precedence over the procedures for formulating and approving physical development plans for urban areas, issuing permits for development, monitoring development activities, taking enforcement actions, and other aspects of urban planning and development.\n\n**Making Regulations**\n**47.**\n(a) The Ministry shall make and enforce all regulations required under this law for its implementation, unless otherwise expressly provided in this law.\n(b) In addition to the matters for which regulations are required to be made under this law, the Ministry shall make regulations concerning the following:\n(1) General regulations for urban planning and development;\n(2) Regulations for defining development controls;\n(3) Regulations concerning the submission of complaints and the adjudication of complaints and imposition of measures;\n(4) Regulations for the registration and classification of planners;\n(5) Regulations for the formation and operation of technical committees, panels, or working groups;\n(6) Regulations for the standards of formulating physical development plans;\n(7) Regulations for the approval, review, and amendment of physical development plans;\n(8) Regulations for the issuance of development permits, and for monitoring the activities of development authorities and taking enforcement measures.\n(c) Regulations required to be made under this law shall be made and published in the Government Gazette within three (3) months from the date this law comes into force.\n\n**Commencement of the Law**\n**48.**\nThis law shall come into force on the date which is three (3) months after it has been passed, ratified, and published in the Government Gazette.\n\n**Definitions**\n**49.**\nUnless the context otherwise requires, the following words and expressions shall have the meanings assigned to them herein:\n(a) \"Ministry\" means the government ministry responsible for the implementation of policies related to urban planning and development at any given time.\n(b) \"Minister\" means the minister of the government ministry responsible for the implementation of policies related to urban planning and development at any given time.\n(c) \"Agriculture\" means the cultivation of grains, vegetables, fruits, and other plant-based products for consumption, as well as the raising of livestock for meat and dairy, and aquaculture, including the propagation and rearing of aquatic organisms. This definition also includes buildings and structures established for agricultural purposes.\n(d) \"Permit for Land Development\" means a permit issued by a planning authority for land development in accordance with a physical development plan.\n(e) \"Physical Development Plan\" means a plan or plans formulated by planning authorities under Article 8 of this law.\n(f) \"Environmental Impact Assessment\" means a report prepared under Act No. 4/93 (Maldives Environmental Protection and Preservation Act) that assesses the environmental impact.\n(g) \"Planning Authority\" means the authorities specified in subsection (b) of Article 6 of this law.\n(h) \"Land\" means the area above dried ground of an island, excluding oil and valuable minerals, and also includes the subsurface portion of the land, all natural growth on the land (excluding cultivated plants and structures), the airspace above the land to a sufficient height for optimal land utilization, and associated air space. This includes:\n(1) Reclaimed land;\n(2) Land adjacent to an island by natural formation;\n(3) Land temporarily submerged due to human activity or natural disaster.\n(i) \"Land Development\" means the construction of buildings, engineering works, excavation or removal of sand, and any other activities carried out on or below the surface of the land, or any changes made to the use of the land or structures thereon. It also includes various types of activities carried out within lagoons and the sea.\n(j) \"Land Zoning\" means the designation of land within a specific area for residential, construction, economic, social, environmental protection, or state purposes under a law.\n(k) \"Planner\" means a person registered under this law to engage in the professional work of planning and designing land or areas for various purposes, including city or island planning and design.\n(l) \"Urban Area\" means areas designated as urban areas under the relevant laws.\n(m) \"City\" means an island or area recognized as a city by the government and published in the Government Gazette.\n(n) \"Island\" means any island declared as an inhabited island by the government under the Decentralization Act of Maldives and published in the Government Gazette.\n(o) \"Garage\" means premises designated for the production and repair of timber and metal products, excluding parking garages for vehicles.\n\n**Law Number: 16/24**\n**Effective from: 08 December 2024**\n\n**Copyright © 2023 Attorney General\u0027s Office**",
